  "text": "The OpenCL 2.0 memory model, which builds on the C11 memory model, is the part of the OpenCL language specification that covers reading and writing shared memory locations. It defines which values are allowed to be read at a given program point, and whether two memory accesses have a data race. It is principally concerned with the collection of atomic functions, which can expose to programmers the various weak memory behaviours of the underlying hardware. The C11 memory model was first formalised by Batty et al. [6] ; this formalisation was then extended to the OpenCL case by Wickerson et al. [CITATION_1] . In §3, we extend the memory model further to formalise OpenCL+RSP.",
